// sigil: 0.1
//
// std/mut_byte_array.sigil â€” Plan C Task 66.6.
//
// **Documentation only.** Like `std/io.sigil`, `std/array.sigil`,
// `std/mut_array.sigil`, and `std/byte_array.sigil`, this file does
// not participate in typecheck. The `MutByteArray` type and its four
// operations are registered at the typechecker as builtins via
// `builtin_types()` and `register_builtin_mut_byte_array_schemes()`.
// `import std.mut_byte_array` is allowed (skip-list path) but is
// not required.
//
// `MutByteArray` is the mutable companion to `ByteArray` (Task 66.5)
// â€” same flat-byte payload, same Boehm-atomic GC layout, but with
// in-place mutation gated through the `Mem` marker effect. Backs
// network buffers, file IO, and any binary construction that wants
// to avoid the O(nÂ˛) repeated-concat shape.
//
// ## Operations
//
// - `mut_byte_array_new(len: Int, fill: Byte) -> MutByteArray ![Mem]`
//   Allocate a fresh mutable byte-array of `len` bytes, each
//   initialised to `fill`.
//
// - `mut_byte_array_length(ba: MutByteArray) -> Int ![Mem]`
//   Read the byte count in O(1).
//
// - `mut_byte_array_get(ba: MutByteArray, i: Int) -> Byte ![Mem]`
//   Read byte `i` in O(1). Aborts on out-of-bounds.
//
// - `mut_byte_array_set(ba: MutByteArray, i: Int, val: Byte) -> Unit ![Mem]`
//   Mutate byte `i` to `val` in place. Aborts on out-of-bounds.
//
// ## Layout
//
// Each `MutByteArray` is `{ header(TAG_MUT_BYTE_ARRAY=0x07,
// count=0, bitmap=0), length: u64, byte[0..N] }`. Identical heap
// shape to `ByteArray` but with a distinct tag so a v2 GC walker
// can apply per-tag write-barrier semantics. v1's Boehm
// conservative collector needs no write barrier (the mark phase
// scans the whole heap conservatively); v2 migration to a precise /
// moving GC will need one.
//
// ## Mem effect gate
//
// `mut_byte_array_*` ops declare `effects: vec!["Mem"]` on their
// builtin schemes; callers without `Mem` in their effect row trip
// E0042 at the call site. `main` declares `![Mem]` to permit
// mutation; the type-level "top-level Mem handler" is the absence
// of a deeper override (Mem has zero ops in v1; see
// `[DEVIATION Task 66]`). Mutation interception via
// `handle Mem.X with` is NOT supported in v1.
//
// ## v1 vs v2
//
// v1 ships the four primitives. A future Plan C task may add
// helpers like `byte_array_to_mut(ba) -> MutByteArray` (clone) and
// `mut_byte_array_freeze(mba) -> ByteArray` (no-clone freeze) once
// the Mem effect grows generic ops in v2.
